          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
            <strong>🇳🇵 Supporters demand reinstatement of the monarchy</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Supporters of Nepal's former king, Gyanendra Shah, gathered in Kathmandu. They were demanding the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-11-03-2025-br1-4-reinstatement-of-the-monarchy" target="_blank">reinstatement of the monarchy</a> and the return of Hinduism as the state religion. They blocked the entrance to Tribhuvan International Airport as Gyanendra arrived from a tour of western Nepal. Despite the peaceful protests, riot police were deployed. Many Nepalis have become disillusioned with the republic because of political instability, corruption, and economic struggles.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Nepal has had 13 governments since the monarchy was abolished in 2008. Gyanendra Shah became the king as a result of the royal massacre that saw nine members of the royal family murdered by the crown prince, Dipendra. Supporters of Gyanendra regret the monarchy's abolition and call for its return. While Gyanendra has not commented on the matter, his chances of regaining power remain slim.</p>
        </mj-text>
